-- Open Text Reaches Record on $1.17 Billion Cloud Buy
-- B y   E r i c   L a m
-- 2013-11-05T22:25:40Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-11-05/open-text-reaches-record-on-1-17-billion-cloud-buy.html
Open Text  Corp.,  Canada ’s second-largest technology company by market value, surged to a record
after agreeing to buy GXS Group Inc. in a deal worth about $1.17
billion to expand its data exchange services business.  Open Text, rose 10 percent to C$85.32 for a market value of
C$5.04 billion ($4.82 billion) at 5:23 p.m. in Toronto, its
highest level since June 1998. Shares in the Waterloo, Ontario-based company rose as much as 13 percent earlier, the biggest
intraday gain since August 2010.  Open Text will pay closely held GXS Group, which provides
cloud-based business-to-business integration services, $1.07
billion in cash and $100 million in stocks, or as much as 2.4
percent of the company’s common shares, the companies said in a
statement. The sale is set to close in 90 days.  Open Text will finance the cash portion of the deal with
$800 million in  debt , along with $265 million in cash on hand.  “The next generation of enterprise software is enterprise-information management,” Mark Barrenechea, chief executive
officer of Open Text, said in the statement. “Today’s GXS
announcement strengthens the information exchange pillar with
the addition of market-leading cloud-based B2B integration
services.”  The deal may add as much as $1.15 in earnings per share to
the company’s fiscal 2015 earnings, Thanos Moschopoulos, a
Toronto-based analyst with BMO Capital Markets, said by e-mail
today.  Open Text “appears to be paying a reasonable purchase
price for what appears to be a stable and very profitable
business,” Moschopoulos said in a note to clients.  Into Cloud  GXS, based in Gaithersburg,  Maryland , has developed cloud-based technologies which streamlines file transfers and allows
companies to manage transactions around the world using the
cloud. It has about 2,900 employees and revenue of $487 million
in 2012, according to the statement.  The deal will add to Open Text’s existing services
including secure e-mail and managed file transfers, Open Text
said.  Cloud technology allows businesses to store data on
Internet-based networks.  To contact the reporter on this story:
